  "text": "The periodic table is literally a cheat sheet. Every single element has its molar mass written right there. Carbon, 12 grams per mole. Oxygen, 16. Hydrogen, 1. That's all you need to know. But what about compounds? Easy. You just add them up. Water, H2O. Hydrogen is 1 times 2. That's 2. Plus oxygen, 16. 18 grams per mole. Carbon dioxide, CO2. Carbon, 12. Plus oxygen, 16 times 2. That's 32. 44 grams per mole. Sulfuric acid, H2SO4. Hydrogen, 1 times 2. 2. Sulfur, 32. Oxygen, 16 times 4. 64. Total, 98 grams per mole. Here's the formula you need to memorize. Moles equals mass divided by molar mass. N equals m over big m. You know, two of those three things? You can find the third. That's it. That's the entire foundation of stoichiometry calculations. Everything builds from here.",
